[]: Shinji as a loose cannon and adolescent rebellion &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by mechashiva &raquo; Sat Nov 15, 2014 5:14 pm Pardon me if I don&#39;t explain my point very well or if its been discussed already but its just something I&#39;d like to touch on because of the larger &quot;How Evangelion is a deconstruction of mecha tropes&quot; article or articles I&#39;m working on. Maybe its my experience with other non-anime forms of media &#40;particularly I mean cop shows or procedurals or certain types of action movies&#41; but the character type of the &quot;loose cannon&quot;: somebody who doesn&#39;t play by the rules or circumvents them to get the job done at the repeated chewings out of his boss BUT it seems a lot of the times, the police captain or whoever&#39;s in a position of authority is doing the yelling can&#39;t really do much about telling Officer So and So he&#39;s &quot;on thin ice&quot;, blah blah blah because even though he caused property damage, he caught the perp and he&#39;s a hero getting his own parade with ticker tape or a key to the city, what have you. There&#39;s not really anything Police Commissioner Hardass can do. How does this relate to Evangelion? Well, its just my analysis but Shinji is a loose cannon character but the world he exists in does not reward him for his behavior like a cop show would. In macro, these kinds of movies/tv shows are power fantasies, about characters who get shouted at for not following rules, doing things their own way, disrespecting authority but still coming out on top in the end by not listening to said authority. One of the ways Evangelion is set up &#40;with outside of the loops otaku Kensuke and Toji, mostly Kensuke being envious of Shinji&#39;s &quot;favored&quot; status&#41; is to make these what would be glamorous, exciting things seem more stifling, scary, stressful and not all that great. Shinji can barely do what he&#39;s asked to do without being injured but he never wakes up in the hospital with flowers or get well cards around his bed. He&#39;s almost always alone. When he does something right, the people at NERV don&#39;t fall all over themselves, calling him a hero. He just did his job and he should be satisfied with that. With his first Angel fight with Sachiel and Shamshel with Kensuke and Toji in his entry plug, it is pretty clear that Shinji has anger issues, in ep. 3 especially he disregards a direct order to retreat from Misato and in a flashback in ep. 4 &#40;the one where he runs away&#41; she is chewing him out over it. I mean, I keep dancing around the point and maybe I&#39;m mistaken in my claim but it seems like in any other mecha anime, this conversation would not be happening or it would be coded to make the main character just seem too cool for rules to apply to him or the ends justified the means. Even just earlier than that in ep. 2 Shinji getting punched in the face by Toji because his little sister being hurt in the fight with Sachiel is something that wouldn&#39;t happen in a mecha anime made to make the main character/audience surrogate feel good about themselves. What do I think this is all leading to or why is the show set up to not overly praise Shinji to boost his ego or brush aside his faults or make him seem more of a badass hero because he doesn&#39;t follow the rules? Because Shinji is teenager meant to learn how to be an adult. Part of growing up means you don&#39;t get a tangible reward for doing something well or you get bailed out for making a mistake and when you&#39;re growing up as a teenager, its hard to get rid of that mentality of entitlement, like the world owes you something or if you throw a tantrum, eventually you get your way. Its carried to its logical extreme in EoTV and EoE and I think its telling that in ep. 18 that Gendo takes control of the EVA-01 &#40;taking away his hands&#41; to take care of the rogue EVA-03 and then later Shinji takes it out on the NERV HQ&#39;s pyramid by stomping on it and Gendo increases the pressure of LCL in Shinji&#39;s entry plug because of his &quot;childish tantrum&quot; &#40;plus its telling that Asuka&#39;s go-to insult for Shinji in 3.33 is to call him a &quot;brat&quot;&#41; At times, EoE feels like locking an angry child in a room to think about what he&#39;s done and he promptly trashes his room and breaks everything because life is not fair. I&#39;m getting a bit sidetracked but I just wanted to comment on it specifically because I re-watched ep. 4 and it struck me as &quot;interesting&quot; that the things Misato says about Shinji after the Shamshel fight COULD be justified in another show but it doesn&#39;t there.

