[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by LordThaeon &raquo; Sat Nov 22, 2014 11:50 pm I disagree. Shinji is rarely disobedient, even when he should take a stand, he passively lets others have their way with him even to where he gets degraded. Just look at his one-sided interactions with Misato and Asuka, hell he didn&#39;t even retaliate or object to Rei&#39;s undeserved slap, he just stood there and took it. He didn&#39;t even hold her accountable later and tell her that what she did was wrong or that his father is not worthy of her respect. The few times where he actually is disobedient and gets talked down for being &quot;a child&quot;, he was actually in the right of things. When he disobeyed Misato during the Shamshel and attacked when told to retreat, that&#39;s really the best that he could have done. Eva was low on power and retreating would just expose himself to getting caught and flung around till he ran out of power and was an easier target. Attacking the angel head-on was a risk as shown when Unit 01 was impaled, but given the circumstances, it was a more viable option than turning your back to an opponent with a range advantage over you. But does Misato reanalyze the situation and conclude that Shinji was right? Perhaps come to an agreement that Shinji was right this time, but he still needs to respect the chain of command and obey orders for his own good? Nope. She bashes and lashes out at him and even goes as far as to tell him to leave... When he&#39;s the only available pilot at that time. But no! It&#39;s Shinji whose wrong for not being a door mat. Then the Bardiel incident was a grand example of Gendo&#39;s failure as a commander when he spaces out the evas where Bardiel can pick them off one by one. But no, it&#39;s Shinji whose in the wrong for objecting to the maiming/murder of another pilot who was his friend. It&#39;s Shinji whose acting like a brat and needs to &quot;grow up&quot;. Then Gendo kicks Shinji out even though the kid is the most essential part of his self-righteous suicide plot and was literally seconds away from getting destroyed by Zeruel before Shinji came back. If anything, it&#39;s people like Gendo, Misato and Asuka who are acting like brats who need to grow up. But instead of holding them accountable or demanding for them to grow up, the story focuses on and punishes the character whose actually making an effort to better himself. But that&#39;s just how I see it. Good find either way.

[]: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Quote Post by ElMariachi &raquo; Sun Nov 23, 2014 6:55 am ^ I think that Gendo being a huge hypocrite with the whole Bardiel debacle was completely intentional, to show us how utterly obsessed by his final goal he is, to the point to have shed out most of his humanity and common sense &#40;you just can&#39;t ask to a rookie pilot to kill another human being just because an Angel is taking it hostage and expect him to obey, hell even Rei was hesitating to follow though his orders!&#41; For disobeying Misato&#39;s order against Shamshel, she told Shinji to fall back toward the mountains so he could recharge the batteries, drop off Touji and Kensuke that were making interferences with the Eva synchronization and think of another attack plan, and they were still out of reach from Shamshel&#39;s laser whips, so yes, Misato&#39;s plan was the sensible thing to do. That doesn&#39;t mean that lashing out at Shinji for disobeying orders like she did was right, simply because she expected him to behave like a trained soldier while he&#39;s still at the level of a militiaman at best, she even lampshades it later when Shinji ran off for a couple of days. &#40;Rebuild made it even more blatant by having her stopping herself dead while lecturing Shinji and slapping herself at the realization that she can&#39;t have that kind of expectation with Shinji as if he was as trained as Rei or Asuka&#41; As for Shinji&#39;s passivity, well yes, that&#39;s part of his character, simply because he isolated himself so much from other people that he doesn&#39;t know how to react or interact with others.

